Faze 1: DATA PRE-PROCESS¶

Normalize Procces¶

I use 5 methods to increase accuracy of the model(Q1 explained here):¶
  • Normalize: by normalizing data,it corrects spaces & semi spaces & apply some other correction to the data.
  • Tokenize: it breaks senteces to words and return a list of words
  • *Stemmer: This option seems to be removing semi-spaces(Nim faseleh). Since it corrupts some words and not work as expected, I don't use it in the proccesing part!
  • Lemmitize: It turns verbs to their 'Bon-e-Maazi' and 'Bon-e-Mozare' format in Farsi. Two verbs having the same Bon mostly have the same concept in a sentence so they can be used instead of each other.
  • Remove Stop-words: By removing most used words that are mostly in all kinds of textes, we decrease unnecessary words count for cheking the data. some of stop-words are like "---- ..."
  • Remove Punctuation-marks: Since puctuations can't be use for analysing the data here, we remove them from the data-set.
In [ ]:
def Normalizer(file_name):
    data_frame = pd.read_csv(file_name)

    def normalize_data_content(content): return normalizer.normalize(content) # normalize contents (correct nim-fasele & spaces & etc)
    
    def tokenizer_data_content(content): return tokenizer.tokenize(content)
    def stemmer_data_content(content): return [stemmer.stem(word) for word in content]
    def remove_stop_words(content): return [word for word in content if word not in stop_words]
    def lemmatizer_data_content(content): return [lemmatizer.lemmatize(word).split('#' , 1)[0] for word in content]

    punctuation_marks={"." , "" , "" , "" , "" , "(" , ")" , "-" , "_", ":" , "!" , '"' , '' , '?'}
    def remove_punctuation_marks(content): return [word for word in content if word not in punctuation_marks]
    
    data_frame['content']=data_frame['content'].apply(normalize_data_content)

    data_frame['content']=data_frame['content'].apply(tokenizer_data_content)
    #data_frame['content']=data_frame['content'].apply(stemmer_data_content) # seems not to work as wanted and corrupt some words
    data_frame['content']=data_frame['content'].apply(remove_stop_words)
    data_frame['content']=data_frame['content'].apply(lemmatizer_data_content) 
    data_frame['content']=data_frame['content'].apply(remove_punctuation_marks)
    data_frame['content']=data_frame['content'].apply(remove_stop_words)
    return data_frame

train_varzeshi_number_of_unique_words=len(list(subjects[''].keys()))
train_salamat_number_of_unique_words=len(list(subjects[''].keys())) 
train_farhangi_number_of_unique_words=len(list(subjects['/'].keys()))

train_fanavari_total_number_of_words=sum(subjects[''].values())
train_havades_total_number_of_words=sum(subjects[''].values())
train_siasi_total_number_of_words=sum(subjects[''].values())
train_varzeshi_total_number_of_words=sum(subjects[''].values())
train_salamat_total_number_of_words=sum(subjects[''].values())
train_farhangi_total_number_of_words=sum(subjects['/'].values())

In this part, we use bayes equation to calculate probabilty of accurance a word in all subjects. $$P(c|x)=\frac{P(x|c)P(c)}{P(x)}$$

Q2:¶

  • posterior: Probabilty of the current subject c by knowing that word x has appeared in the content.
  • prior: Probability of subject c
  • likelihood: Probabilty of seeing the word x knowing that the subject is c
  • evidence: Probabilty of seeing the word x
Q3:¶

Bigrams:
Ex.:

  • \

In the above sentences, '' has two diffrent meaning and can make confusion if we use unigram method since we won't know what meaning it has for sure. Therefore we can use Bigrams to match either '' or '' to the ''. if we use longer n-gram, it results in better assumption of the meaning of the words but it can make calculations harder.
Note: In this project, we use only unigram!

Q4:¶

When we use naive bayes equation to calculate probabilty of words, some of the words that appear in one or more subjects, don't exist on other subject(s). Therefore, the probabilty of that word is equal to zero! $$P(x|c)=0$$ Because of this, even if other words matches greatly to one subject,this subject probabilty equals to zero hence the it multiplies to probabilty of x knowing subject is c that equals to zero!

Q5:¶

Solution to the above problem is by using Additive Smoothing.
To avoid multiply zero, we give a little probablity to this words and for not corrupting the probabilties, we use this equation instead:

|V|= number of unique words

def evaluation_without_additive_smoothing(test_data_frame):

    _=0
    Detected_Class={'': 0,'':0,'':0,'':0,'':0,'/':0}
    __s={'': 0,'':0,'':0,'':0,'':0,'/':0}
    Total_Class={'': 0,'':0,'':0,'':0,'':0,'/':0}

    for index,data in test_data_frame.iterrows():
        chances={'': 1,'':1,'':1,'':1,'':1,'/':1}
        for word in data.content:
            if word in subjects['']:
                chances[''] *= (subjects[''][word]/train_havades_total_number_of_words)
            else:
                chances['']=0

            if word in subjects['']:
                chances[''] *= (subjects[''][word]/train_fanavari_total_number_of_words)
            else:
                chances['']=0

            if word in subjects['']:
                chances[''] *= (subjects[''][word]/train_salamat_total_number_of_words)
            else:
                chances['']=0

            if word in subjects['']:
                chances[''] *= (subjects[''][word]/train_siasi_total_number_of_words)
            else:
                chances['']=0

            if word in subjects['']:
                chances[''] *= (subjects[''][word]/train_varzeshi_total_number_of_words)
            else:
                chances['']=0

            if word in subjects['/']:
                chances['/'] *= (subjects['/'][word]/train_farhangi_total_number_of_words)
            else:
                chances['/']=0
        

        max_chance=max(chances,key=chances.get)
        if(max_chance==data.label):
            Correct_Detected_Class[data.label]+=1
            _+=1
        Detected_Class[max_chance]+=1
        Total_Class[data.label]+=1
            
        

            
    return Correct_Detected,Detected_Class,Correct_Detected_Class,Total_Class

Faze 3: EVALUATION¶

Q7¶

If the code detects a few classes out of a large data-set,for example 5 out of 10000 subjects,then the Percision might be 100% but actualy our code sucks.
On the other hand, if our code detecs large number of subjects as one particular subject(for example our code predicts all subjects are ''),then Recall might be 100% but our code still sucks.

Q8¶

F1 Score is the harmonic mean of Precision and Recall. Therefore, this score takes both false positives and false negatives into account. Intuitively it is not as easy to understand as accuracy, but F1 is usually more useful than accuracy, especially if you have an uneven class distribution. Accuracy works best if false positives and false negatives have similar cost. If the cost of false positives and false negatives are very different, its better to look at both Precision and Recall.

Q9¶

Micro: computes f1 by value total true positives, false negatives and false positives (no matter of the prediction for each label in the dataset)

Macro: computess f1 for each label, and returns the average without considering the proportion for each label in the dataset.

Weighted: computes f1 for each label, and returns the average considering the proportion for each label in the dataset.

With Additive Smoothing Test¶

In [ ]:
def evaluation_with_additive_smoothing(test_data_frame):
    _=0
    Detected_Class={'': 0,'':0,'':0,'':0,'':0,'/':0}
    __s={'': 0,'':0,'':0,'':0,'':0,'/':0}
    Total_Class={'': 0,'':0,'':0,'':0,'':0,'/':0}

    for index,data in test_data_frame.iterrows():
        chances={'': 1,'':1,'':1,'':1,'':1,'/':1}
        for word in data.content:
            chances[''] += ((subjects[''].get(word,0)+1) / (train_havades_total_number_of_words+train_havades_number_of_unique_words))
            
            chances[''] += ((subjects[''].get(word,0)+1) / (train_fanavari_total_number_of_words+train_fanavari_number_of_unique_words))       
          
            chances[''] += ((subjects[''].get(word,0)+1) / (train_salamat_total_number_of_words+train_salamat_number_of_unique_words))
   
            chances[''] += ((subjects[''].get(word,0)+1) / (train_siasi_total_number_of_words+train_siasi_number_of_unique_words))
       
            chances[''] += ((subjects[''].get(word,0)+1) / (train_varzeshi_total_number_of_words+train_varzeshi_number_of_unique_words))
         
            chances['/'] += ((subjects['/'].get(word,0)+1) / (train_farhangi_total_number_of_words+train_farhangi_number_of_unique_words))
  
        
        
        max_chance=max(chances,key=chances.get)
        if(max_chance==data.label):
            Correct_Detected_Class[data.label]+=1
            _+=1
        else:
            wrong_datas.append((data.content,data.label,max_chance))
        Detected_Class[max_chance]+=1
        Total_Class[data.label]+=1
            
        

            
    return Correct_Detected,Detected_Class,Correct_Detected_Class,Total_Class
